<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="500" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,313]" pageId="3" pageNumber="500">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,152,175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="500">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ismay" authorityYear="2017" box="[532,625,151,175]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Psilacrum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="500" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lineatum">
<emphasis box="[532,625,151,175]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="500">lineatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(of a line) is derived from Latin, referring to the stripe in the middle of the scutum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="500" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,313]" pageId="3" pageNumber="500">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,221,244]" pageId="3" pageNumber="500">Comments.</emphasis>
We have seen two females from Rio Grande, which have a different color-pattern on the scutum, and are therefore excluded from the 
<typeStatus box="[498,544,256,279]" pageId="3" pageNumber="500">type</typeStatus>
series. The black central stripe is lacking and the pair of lateral spots is very long. Males are needed to confirm their identity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
